ovec offers an engaging study that asks us to consider the broader environmental sustainability of health care. Through a comparative analysis of the care provided to terminally ill patients in a conventional cancer ward, a palliative care unit, and an acute-care hospice facility, she shows how decisions made at a patient’s bedside govern the environmental footprint of the healthcare industry. Likewise, Dying Green offers insights on the many opportunities that exist for reducing the ecological impacts of medical practices in general, while also enhancing care for the dying in particular. By envisioning a more sustainable approach to care, this book offers a way forward that is better for both patients and the planet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMedical carexEnvironmental aspects. 0aMedical economics. 0aMedical wastesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSustainability. 0aTerminal carexEconomic aspects. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  acancer, death, end-of-life, care, health care, health, policy, health policy, end of life, end-of-life care, hospital, medicine, medical care, costs, economy, environment, ecology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2023 Englishz978311131910008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2023z9783111318141oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883214540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978832145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978832145/original  a978-3-11-131910-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2023 En